Optionally return pending UO in `eth_getUserOperationByHash` (#382)

This change allows a bundler to return a non-null value for `eth_getUserOperationByHash` when the requrested UO is pending in its mempool. In this case the bundler can populate the same return object as when the UO is mined, but with `blockNumber`, `blockHash`, and `transactionHash` set to `null`.

AA-162 Inconsistent userOpHash (#245)

* Inconsistent userOpHash

As reported in #237, userOpHash might be manipulated by a caller.
While this is not a security vulnerability of any other account, it does
cause inconsistency in the output of external tools such as block explorers.
It might also cause applications that rely on the userOpHash uniqueness to fail

* use UserOp.hash()

* PR comments

Re-base gascheck (#252)

Change the base for "gascheck"
This is not a change in the contracts, but in the scripts to calculate the gas usage.
The default sample call now calls entryPoint() in the account, which returns a constant (entrypoint) instead of a variable (nonce)
The 2000 extra gas overhead seen results/gas-checker.txt in gas is actually a fix of a mistake: previously, accessing the "nonce" field was attributed to the "exec" call (because we called "nonce()"). Now it is rightfully attributed to the validation, not execution.

- BLSAccount (and any other account using signature-aggregator) must verify the public key in the initCode (as last 4 words, just as the BLSAggregator checks)

gas limit on postOp (#36)

* gas limit on postOp

- when a paymaster is used, it has a limit of verificationGas.
- our security might call it twice.
- the calculation of maximum gas per op in case of a paymaster is thus
preVerificationGas + verificationGas*3 + callGas
- (without a paymaster the maximum gas limit stayed the same.
- the above calculation is done by the entryPoint, but should also be
used by the minter, to provide enough gas to handleOp.

* add gas validations to sample paymasters

Re-base gascheck (#252)

Change the base for "gascheck"
This is not a change in the contracts, but in the scripts to calculate the gas usage.
The default sample call now calls entryPoint() in the account, which returns a constant (entrypoint) instead of a variable (nonce)
The 2000 extra gas overhead seen results/gas-checker.txt in gas is actually a fix of a mistake: previously, accessing the "nonce" field was attributed to the "exec" call (because we called "nonce()"). Now it is rightfully attributed to the validation, not execution.
